<h2 id=3D"hid2" class=3D"subsection">Review of the basics of statistical in=
ference</h2>
<p>
   Remember the main elements of a
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/fundamentals-of-statistics/statisti=
cal-inference">statistical
   inference</a> problem:
</p>
<ol>
   <li>
      <p>
         we observe some data (a sample), that we collect in a vector
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"21" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"x" style=3D"background-position:0px -2309px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>;
      </p>
   </li>
   <li>
      <p>
         we regard
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"21" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"x" style=3D"background-position:0px -2309px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>
         as the  <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/glossary/realization-o=
f-a-random-variable">realization</a>
         of a  <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/fundamentals-of-probabil=
ity/random-vectors">random vector</a>
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"13" height=3D"21" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"X" style=3D"background-position:0px -2167px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>;
      </p>
   </li>
   <li>
      <p>
         we do not know the probability distribution of
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"13" height=3D"21" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"X" style=3D"background-position:0px -2167px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>
         (i.e., the distribution that generated our sample);
      </p>
   </li>
   <li>
      <p>
         we define a statistical model, that is, a set
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"15" height=3D"21" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$Phi $" style=3D"background-position:0px -2122px;=
vertical-align:-5px"></span>
         of probability distributions that could have generated the data;
      </p>
   </li>
   <li>
      <p>
         optionally, we parametrize the model, that is, we put the elements=
 of
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"15" height=3D"21" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$Phi $" style=3D"background-position:0px -2101px;=
vertical-align:-5px"></span>
         in correspondence with a set of real vectors called parameters;
      </p>
   </li>
   <li>
      <p>
         we use the sample and the statistical model to make a statement (a=
n inference)
         about the unknown data generating distribution (or about the param=
eter that
         corresponds to it).
      </p>
   </li>
</ol>
<p>
   In Bayesian inference, we assign a subjective distribution to the elemen=
ts of
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"15" height=3D"21" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$Phi $" style=3D"background-position:0px -2122px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>,
   and then we use the data to derive a posterior distribution.
</p>
<p>
   In parametric Bayesian inference, the subjective distribution is assigne=
d to
   the  <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/glossary/parameter">parameters<=
/a> that are put into
   correspondence with the elements of
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"15" height=3D"21" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$Phi $" style=3D"background-position:0px -2122px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>.
</p>
<h2 id=3D"hid3" class=3D"subsection">The likelihood</h2>
<p>
   The first building block of a parametric Bayesian model is the
   likelihood<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"67" heigh=
t=3D"38" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAAL=
AAAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq1]" style=3D"background-position:0px=
 -1116px;"></span>
</p>
<p>
   The likelihood is equal to the
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/glossary/probability-density-functi=
on">probability density</a> of
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"21" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"x" style=3D"background-position:0px -2309px;vertical-al=
ign:-5px"></span>
   when the parameter of the data generating distribution is equal to
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$	heta $" style=3D"background-position:0px -2285px;vert=
ical-align:-5px"></span>.
</p>
<p>
   For the time being, we assume that
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"21" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"x" style=3D"background-position:0px -2309px;vertical-al=
ign:-5px"></span>
   and
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$	heta $" style=3D"background-position:0px -2237px;vert=
ical-align:-5px"></span>
   are  <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/glossary/absolutely-continuous-=
random-variable">continuous</a>.
   Later, we will discuss how to relax this assumption.
</p>
<h3 id=3D"hid4" class=3D"subsubsection">Example</h3>
<p>
   Suppose that the sample
   <span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"152" height=3D"48" =
src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAA=
EAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq2]" style=3D"background-position:0px -776px;"=
></span>is
   a vector of
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"n" style=3D"background-position:0px -2213px;vertical-al=
ign:-5px"></span>
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/glossary/IID-sequence">independent =
and identically distributed</a>
   draws
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"64" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq3]" style=3D"background-position:0px -1303px;vertica=
l-align:-5px"></span>
   from a  <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/probability-distributions/no=
rmal-distribution">normal
   distribution</a>.
</p>
<p>
   The mean
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"12" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"mu" style=3D"background-position:0px -2188px;vertical-a=
lign:-5px"></span>
   of the distribution is unknown, while its variance
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"21" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"sigma^2" style=3D"background-position:0px -1861px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>
   is known. These are the two parameters of the model.
</p>
<p>
   The probability density function of a generic draw
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"16" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$x_{i}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -2077px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>
   is<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp2" width=3D"299" height=3D"5=
8" src=3D"https://www.statlect.com/images/Bayesian-inference__20.png" alt=
=3D"[eq4]"></span>where
   we use the notation
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"49" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq5]" style=3D"background-position:0px -1400px;vertica=
l-align:-5px"></span>
   to highlight the fact that
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"12" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"mu" style=3D"background-position:0px -2188px;vertical-a=
lign:-5px"></span>
   is unknown and the density of
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"16" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$x_{i}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -2077px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>
   depends on this unknown parameter.
</p>
<p>
   Because the observations
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"64" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq6]" style=3D"background-position:0px -1303px;vertica=
l-align:-5px"></span>
   are
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/fundamentals-of-probability/indepen=
dent-random-variables">independent</a>,
   we can write the likelihood as
   <span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp2" width=3D"426" height=3D"66"=
 src=3D"https://www.statlect.com/images/Bayesian-inference__25.png" alt=3D"=
[eq7]"></span>
</p>
<h2 id=3D"hid5" class=3D"subsection">The prior</h2>
<p>
   The second building block of a Bayesian model is the
   prior<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"67" height=3D"=
38" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAA=
ABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq8]" style=3D"background-position:0px -124=
0px;"></span>
</p>
<p>
   The prior is the subjective probability density assigned to the paramete=
r
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$	heta $" style=3D"background-position:0px -2285px;vert=
ical-align:-5px"></span>.
</p>
<h3 id=3D"hid6" class=3D"subsubsection">Example</h3>
<p>
   Let us continue the previous example.
</p>
<p>
   The statistician believes that the parameter
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"12" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"mu" style=3D"background-position:0px -2188px;vertical-a=
lign:-5px"></span>
   is most likely equal to
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"20" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$mu _{0}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -1960px;ver=
tical-align:-5px"></span>
   and that values of
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"12" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"mu" style=3D"background-position:0px -2188px;vertical-a=
lign:-5px"></span>
   very far from
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"20" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$mu _{0}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -1935px;ver=
tical-align:-5px"></span>
   are quite unlikely.
</p>
<p>
   She expresses this belief about the parameter
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"12" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"mu" style=3D"background-position:0px -2188px;vertical-a=
lign:-5px"></span>
   by assigning to it a normal distribution with mean
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"20" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$mu _{0}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -1935px;ver=
tical-align:-5px"></span>
   and variance
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"18" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$	au ^{2}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -1985px;ve=
rtical-align:-5px"></span>.
</p>
<p>
   So, the prior
   is<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp2" width=3D"283" height=3D"5=
8" src=3D"https://www.statlect.com/images/Bayesian-inference__35.png" alt=
=3D"[eq9]"></span>
</p>
<h2 id=3D"hid7" class=3D"subsection">The prior predictive distribution</h2>
<p>
   After specifying the prior and the likelihood, we can derive the
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/glossary/marginal-probability-densi=
ty-function">marginal
   density</a> of
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"21" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"x" style=3D"background-position:0px -2309px;vertical-al=
ign:-5px"></span>:<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"158"=
 height=3D"134" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BA=
EAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq10]" style=3D"background-posi=
tion:0px -514px;"></span>where:
   in step
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"17" height=3D"34" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$=0Crame{A}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -2043px;=
vertical-align:-8px"></span>
   we perform the so-called marginalization (see the lecture on
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/fundamentals-of-probability/random-=
vectors">random vectors</a>); in
   step
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"17" height=3D"34" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$=0Crame{B}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -2009px;=
vertical-align:-8px"></span>
   we use the fact that a
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/glossary/joint-probability-density-=
function">joint density</a> can
   be written as the product of a conditional and a marginal density (see t=
he
   lecture on
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/fundamentals-of-probability/conditi=
onal-probability-distributions">conditional
   probability distributions</a>).
</p>
<p>
   The
   notation<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"67" height=
=3D"48" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALA=
AAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq11]" style=3D"background-position:0px=
 -1192px;"></span>is
   a shorthand for the multiple
   integral<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"89" height=
=3D"76" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALA=
AAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq12]" style=3D"background-position:0px=
 -1040px;"></span>where
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"14" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"K" style=3D"background-position:0px -2143px;vertical-al=
ign:-5px"></span>
   is the dimension of the parameter vector
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$	heta $" style=3D"background-position:0px -2237px;vert=
ical-align:-5px"></span>.
</p>
<p>
   The marginal density of
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"21" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"x" style=3D"background-position:0px -2309px;vertical-al=
ign:-5px"></span>,
   derived in the manner above, is called the <strong>prior predictive
   distribution</strong>. Roughly speaking, it is the probability distribut=
ion
   that we assign to the data
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"21" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"x" style=3D"background-position:0px -2309px;vertical-al=
ign:-5px"></span>
   before observing it.
</p>
<h3 id=3D"hid8" class=3D"subsubsection">Example</h3>
<p>
   Given the prior and the posterior specified in the previous two examples=
,
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/fundamentals-of-statistics/normal-d=
istribution-Bayesian-estimation">it
   can be proved</a> that the prior predictive distribution is
   <span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp2" width=3D"581" height=3D"96"=
 src=3D"https://www.statlect.com/images/Bayesian-inference__46.png" alt=3D"=
[eq13]"></span>where
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"7" height=3D"24" src=3D"d=
ata:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICRA=
EAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"i" style=3D"background-position:0px -2379px;vertical-ali=
gn:-5px"></span>
   is an
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"36" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$n	imes 1$" style=3D"background-position:0px -1621px;ve=
rtical-align:-5px"></span>
   vector of ones, and
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"8" height=3D"24" src=3D"d=
ata:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICRA=
EAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"I" style=3D"background-position:0px -2355px;vertical-ali=
gn:-5px"></span>
   is the
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"36" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$n	imes n$" style=3D"background-position:0px -1597px;ve=
rtical-align:-5px"></span>
   identity matrix.
</p>
<p>
   Hence, the prior predictive distribution of
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"21" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"x" style=3D"background-position:0px -2309px;vertical-al=
ign:-5px"></span>
   is
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/probability-distributions/multivari=
ate-normal-distribution">multivariate
   normal</a> with mean
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"24" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$imu _{0}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -1812px;ve=
rtical-align:-5px"></span>
   and  <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/fundamentals-of-probability/cov=
ariance-matrix">covariance
   matrix</a>
   <span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp2" width=3D"210" height=3D"52"=
 src=3D"https://www.statlect.com/images/Bayesian-inference__53.png" alt=3D"=
[eq14]"></span>
</p>
<p>
   Thus, under the prior predictive distribution, a draw
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"16" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$x_{i}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -2077px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>
   has mean
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"20" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$mu _{0}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -1910px;ver=
tical-align:-5px"></span>,
   variance
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"52" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq15]" style=3D"background-position:0px -1376px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>
   and covariance with the other draws equal to
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"18" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$	au ^{2}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -1985px;ve=
rtical-align:-5px"></span>.
</p>
<p>
   The covariance is induced by the fact that the mean parameter
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"12" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"mu" style=3D"background-position:0px -2188px;vertical-a=
lign:-5px"></span>,
   which is stochastic, is the same for all draws.
</p>
<h2 id=3D"hid9" class=3D"subsection">The posterior</h2>
<p>
   After observing the data
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"21" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"x" style=3D"background-position:0px -2309px;vertical-al=
ign:-5px"></span>,
   we use Bayes' rule to update the prior about the parameter
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$	heta $" style=3D"background-position:0px -2237px;vert=
ical-align:-5px"></span>:<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=
=3D"155" height=3D"52" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wA=
AACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq16]" style=3D"backgrou=
nd-position:0px -648px;"></span>
</p>
<p>
   The conditional density
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"44" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq17]" style=3D"background-position:0px -1547px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>
   is called posterior distribution of the parameter.
</p>
<p>
   By using the formula for the marginal density
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"32" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$pleft( x
ight) $" style=3D"background-position:0px -1691px;vertical-align:-5px"></sp=
an>
   derived above, we
   obtain<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp2" width=3D"185" height=
=3D"62" src=3D"https://www.statlect.com/images/Bayesian-inference__64.png" =
alt=3D"[eq18]"></span>
</p>
<p>
   Thus, the posterior depends on the two distributions specified by the
   statistician, the prior
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"32" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq19]" style=3D"background-position:0px -1666px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>
   and the likelihood
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"44" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq20]" style=3D"background-position:0px -1522px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>.
</p>
<h3 id=3D"hid10" class=3D"subsubsection">Example</h3>
<p>
   In the normal model of the previous examples,
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/fundamentals-of-statistics/normal-d=
istribution-Bayesian-estimation">it
   can be proved</a> that the posterior
   is<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp2" width=3D"298" height=3D"5=
8" src=3D"https://www.statlect.com/images/Bayesian-inference__67.png" alt=
=3D"[eq21]"></span>where<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp2" width=
=3D"341" height=3D"112" src=3D"https://www.statlect.com/images/Bayesian-inf=
erence__68.png" alt=3D"[eq22]"></span>
</p>
<p>
   Thus, the posterior distribution of
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"12" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"mu" style=3D"background-position:0px -2188px;vertical-a=
lign:-5px"></span>
   is normal with mean
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"20" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$mu _{n}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -1885px;ver=
tical-align:-5px"></span>
   and variance
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"21" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$sigma _{n}^{2}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -183=
7px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>.
</p>
<p>
   The posterior mean
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"20" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$mu _{n}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -1885px;ver=
tical-align:-5px"></span>
   is a weighted average of:
</p>
<ul>
   <li>
      <p>
         the mean of the observed data
         (<span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"65" height=3D"25" =
src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAA=
EAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq23]" style=3D"background-position:0px -1278px=
;vertical-align:-7px"></span>);
      </p>
   </li>
   <li>
      <p>
         the prior mean
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"20" height=3D"25" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$mu _{0}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -1935=
px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>.
      </p>
   </li>
</ul>
<p>
   The weights are inversely proportional to the variances of the two means=
:
</p>
<ul>
   <li>
      <p>
         if the prior variance
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"18" height=3D"24" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$	au ^{2}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -198=
5px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>
         is high, then the prior mean
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"20" height=3D"25" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$mu _{0}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -1910=
px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>
         receives little weight;
      </p>
   </li>
   <li>
      <p>
         by the same token, if the variance of the sample mean (which is eq=
ual to
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"33" height=3D"21" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$sigma ^{2}/n$" style=3D"background-position:0px =
-1645px;vertical-align:-5px"></span>)
         is high, then the sample mean receives little weight and more weig=
ht is
         assigned to the prior.
      </p>
   </li>
</ul>
<p>
   Both the sample mean and the prior mean provide information about
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"12" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"mu" style=3D"background-position:0px -2188px;vertical-a=
lign:-5px"></span>.
   They are combined together, but more weight is given to the signal that =
has
   higher precision (smaller variance).
</p>
<p>
   When the sample size
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"n" style=3D"background-position:0px -2213px;vertical-al=
ign:-5px"></span>
   becomes very large (goes to infinity), then all the weight is given to t=
he
   information coming from the sample (the sample mean) and no weight is gi=
ven to
   the prior. This is typical of Bayesian inference.
</p>
