data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$=0Crame{B}$" style=3D"background-position:0px -2009px;=
vertical-align:-8px"></span>
   we use the fact that the integral of a density (over the whole support) =
is
   equal to
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"1" style=3D"background-position:0px -2261px;vertical-al=
ign:-5px"></span>.
</p>
<p>
   In summary, when we multiply the posterior by a function that does not d=
epend
   on
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$	heta $" style=3D"background-position:0px -2237px;vert=
ical-align:-5px"></span>
   (but may depend on
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"21" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"x" style=3D"background-position:0px -2309px;vertical-al=
ign:-5px"></span>),
   we obtain a function
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"48" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq40]" style=3D"background-position:0px -1425px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>
   proportional to the posterior.
</p>
<p>
   If we divide the new function
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"48" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq38]" style=3D"background-position:0px -1450px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>
   by its integral, then we recover the posterior.
</p>
<h2 id=3D"hid15" class=3D"subsection">The posterior is proportional to the =
prior times the likelihood</h2>
<p>
   In the posterior
   formula<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp2" width=3D"216" height=
=3D"62" src=3D"https://www.statlect.com/images/Bayesian-inference__132.png"=
 alt=3D"[eq42]"></span>the
   marginal
   density<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"163" height=
=3D"48" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALA=
AAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq43]" style=3D"background-position:0px=
 -151px;"></span>does
   not depend on
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$	heta $" style=3D"background-position:0px -2237px;vert=
ical-align:-5px"></span>
   (because
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$	heta $" style=3D"background-position:0px -2237px;vert=
ical-align:-5px"></span>
   is "integrated out").
</p>
<p>
   Thus, by using the notation introduced in the previous section, we can
   write<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"151" height=3D=
"38" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAA=
AABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq44]" style=3D"background-position:0px -8=
62px;"></span>that
   is, the posterior
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"44" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq17]" style=3D"background-position:0px -1547px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>
   is proportional to the prior
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"32" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq19]" style=3D"background-position:0px -1666px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>
   times the likelihood
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"44" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq20]" style=3D"background-position:0px -1522px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>.
</p>
<p>
   Both
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"44" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq48]" style=3D"background-position:0px -1572px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>
   and
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"32" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq49]" style=3D"background-position:0px -1738px;vertic=
al-align:-5px"></span>
   are known because they are specified by the statistician.
</p>
<p>
   Thus, the posterior (which we want to compute) is proportional to the pr=
oduct
   of two known quantities.
</p>
<p>
   This proportionality to two known quantities is extremely important in
   Bayesian inference: various methods allow us to exploit it in order to c=
ompute
   the posterior when (2) cannot be calculated and hence (1) cannot be work=
ed out
   directly.
</p>
<h2 id=3D"hid16" class=3D"subsection">Factorization</h2>
<p>
   Often, we are not able to apply Bayes' rule
   <span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"155" height=3D"52" =
src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAA=
EAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq50]" style=3D"background-position:0px -648px;=
"></span>because
   we cannot derive the marginal distribution
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"32" height=3D"25" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$pleft( x
ight) $" style=3D"background-position:0px -1691px;vertical-align:-5px"></sp=
an>
   analytically.
</p>
<p>
   However, we are sometimes able to write the joint
   distribution<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"151" he=
ight=3D"38" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAA=
AALAAAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq51]" style=3D"background-position=
:0px -824px;"></span>as<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D=
"153" height=3D"38" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAAC=
H5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq52]" style=3D"background-=
position:0px -700px;"></span>where:
</p>
<ul>
   <li>
      <p>
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"32" height=3D"22" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$hleft( x
ight) $" style=3D"background-position:0px -1716px;vertical-align:-5px"></sp=
an>
         is a function that depends only on
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"21" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"x" style=3D"background-position:0px -2309px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>;
      </p>
   </li>
   <li>
      <p>
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"46" height=3D"22" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq53]" style=3D"background-position:0px -1500px;=
vertical-align:-5px"></span>
         is a probability density (or mass) function of
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"24" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$	heta $" style=3D"background-position:0px -2237p=
x;vertical-align:-5px"></span>
         (for any fixed
         <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"21" s=
rc=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAE=
AAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"x" style=3D"background-position:0px -2309px;verti=
cal-align:-5px"></span>).
      </p>
   </li>
</ul>
<p>
   If we can work out this factorization,
   then<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"122" height=3D"=
64" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAA=
ABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq54]" style=3D"background-position:0px -97=
6px;"></span>
</p>
<p>
   See the lecture on the
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/fundamentals-of-probability/factori=
zation-of-joint-probability-density-functions">factorization
   of probability density functions</a> for a proof of this fact.
</p>
<h2 id=3D"hid17" class=3D"subsection">MCMC</h2>
<p>
   There are several Bayesian models that allow us to compute the posterior
   distribution of the parameters analytically. However, this is often not
   possible.
</p>
<p>
   When an analytical solution is not available, Markov Chain Monte Carlo (=
MCMC)
   methods are commonly employed to derive the posterior distribution
   numerically.
</p>
<p>
   MCMC methods are  <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/asymptotic-theory/=
Monte-Carlo-method">Monte Carlo
   methods</a> that allow us to generate large samples of correlated draws =
from
   the posterior distribution of the parameter vector by simply using the
   proportionality<span class=3D"displayed"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"151"=
 height=3D"38" src=3D"data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAE=
AAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICRAEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"[eq55]" style=3D"background-posit=
ion:0px -862px;"></span>
</p>
<p>
   The  <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/asymptotic-theory/empirical-dis=
tribution">empirical
   distribution</a> of the generated sample can then be used to produce
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/asymptotic-theory/plug-in-principle=
">plug-in estimates</a> of the
   quantities of interest.
</p>
<p>
   See the lecture on
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/fundamentals-of-statistics/Markov-C=
hain-Monte-Carlo">MCMC
   methods</a> for more details.
</p>
<h2 id=3D"hid18" class=3D"subsection">Quantities of interest</h2>
<p>
   After updating the prior, we can use the posterior distribution of
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$	heta $" style=3D"background-position:0px -2237px;vert=
ical-align:-5px"></span>
   to make statements about the parameter
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$	heta $" style=3D"background-position:0px -2237px;vert=
ical-align:-5px"></span>
   or about quantities that depend on
   <span class=3D"inm"><img class=3D"sp" width=3D"11" height=3D"24" src=3D"=
data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAANvf7wAAACH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAICR=
AEAOw=3D=3D" alt=3D"$	heta $" style=3D"background-position:0px -2237px;vert=
ical-align:-5px"></span>.
</p>
<p>
   The quantities about which we make a statement are often called
   <strong>quantities of interest</strong> (e.g.,  <a href=3D"https://www.s=
tatlect.com/fundamentals-of-statistics/Bayesian-inference#Bernardo">Bernard=
o
   and Smith 2009</a>) or <strong>objects of interest </strong>(e.g.,
    <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/fundamentals-of-statistics/Bayesian=
-inference#Geweke">Geweke 2005</a>).
</p>
<p>
   The Bayesian approach provides us with a posterior probability distribut=
ion of
   the quantity of interest. We are free to summarize that distribution in =
any
   way that we deem convenient.
</p>
<p>
   For example, we can:
</p>
<ul>
   <li>
      <p>
         plot the probability density (or mass) of the quantity of interest=
;
      </p>
   </li>
   <li>
      <p>
         report the mean of the distribution (as our best guess of the true=
 value of
         the quantity of interest) and its
          <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/glossary/standard-deviation">=
standard deviation</a> (as a measure
         of dispersion of our posterior beliefs);
      </p>
   </li>
   <li>
      <p>
         report the probability that the quantity of interest (say, a param=
eter) is
         equal (or very close) to a certain value which had previously been
         hypothesized (similarly to what is done in
          <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/fundamentals-of-statistics/hy=
pothesis-testing">hypothesis
         testing</a>).
      </p>
</li>
</ul>

<h2 id=3D"hid19" class=3D"subsection">More examples of Bayesian inference</=
h2>
<p>
   Now that you know about the basics of Bayesian inference, you can study =
two
   applications in the following lectures:
</p>
<ul>
   <li>
      <p>
          <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/fundamentals-of-statistics/no=
rmal-distribution-Bayesian-estimation">Bayesian
         inference about the parameters of a normal distribution</a>, where=
 we prove
         all the formulae shown in the examples above;
      </p>
   </li>
   <li>
      <p>
          <a href=3D"https://www.statlect.com/fundamentals-of-statistics/Ba=
yesian-regression">Bayesian inference
         about the parameters of a linear regression model</a>.
      </p>
</li>
</ul>

